an a general theory of racial attitudes become possible. Most importantly, he shows that a strict notion of racial identification in black and white cannot be assumed universal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBlacksxRace identityxBrazil. 0aBlacksxRace identityzBrazil. 0aEthnic attitudesxBrazil. 0aEthnic attitudeszBrazil. 0aRace awarenessxBrazil. 0aRace awarenesszBrazil. 0aRacexGovernment policyxBrazil. 0aRacexGovernment policyzBrazil. 0aRacially mixed peoplexRace identityxBrazil. 0aRacially mixed peoplexRace identityzBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477626440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804776264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804776264.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles